AUDIO: 'Ideogram has just open-sourced Ideogram 4, their very first open-weight image model. And honestly, if your work involves posters, logos, typography, branding, or layout design, this might be one of the most important local AI'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'models to watch in 2026. Because for the first time, it\'s starting to feel less like just another AI image model, and more like a real AI design tool. In this video, I\'ll show you how to run it'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'locally on a PC with only 8 GB of VRAM and 32 GB of RAM, and how I modified the workflow to avoid constant OOM crashes. The workflow, model links, JSON prompts, and all related resources used in this'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video are available on Patreon. Let\'s get started. Hello. Welcome to Smart Vision. On this channel, I keep sharing the latest AI tutorials and practical tools. All workflows, materials, and resources'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from this video are on my Patreon, and are available to download after you register. For supporters, I provide extra professional tools and deeper guides. If you like this content, consider'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscribing and supporting the channel. Now, let\'s get started. All right. Before diving into the settings, let\'s look at the results first. For this image, I only used a very basic prompt. An orange cat wearing'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a tiny wizard hat sitting at a wooden desk reading a magic book, warm candlelight, fantasy library background. And even with such a simple English description, the overall quality from Ideogram 4 is already surprisingly high.'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The fur detail, lighting atmosphere, even the tiny text on the book pages, all feel more stable than many other models. But this is actually just its basic mode. Now, let\'s take the exact same concept,'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but first let a local LLM convert it into structured JSON before feeding it into Ideogram. And this is where the difference becomes very obvious. It\'s no longer just understanding a sentence. It actually'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'starts behaving more like design software arranging a composition. Character placement, main light direction, background layering, color style, camera language, everything becomes more consistent and intentional. A lot of image models are basically'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guessing what you mean, but Ideogram feels more like it\'s executing a specification sheet. Especially when it comes to composition and art direction, the gap becomes extremely noticeable. But the thing that really separates it'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from other models for me is poster generation. And I don\'t mean AI images that kind of look like posters. I mean something much closer to actual design generation. For example, I can explicitly define title content, color palettes, layout'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'structure, and even use an LLM to generate design-oriented JSON descriptions automatically. That changes the entire workflow. Because previously, most models were generating an image,'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but Ideogram is starting to generate a design document. And if you\'ve worked with AI design before, you already know how painful this used to be. Older models generating English titles felt like pulling a gotcha. You type summer sale,'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and the model gives you sun mer sela. But Ideogram 4 clearly isn\'t just another AI art model anymore. It\'s moving toward becoming a real AI design tool. Ideogram 4 is a 9.3 billion parameter'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image generation model. But the important part isn\'t its size. What matters is it wasn\'t built by fine-tuning SDXL or flux. A lot of current models are essentially'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modified versions of older architectures, but Ideogram feels much more like a system redesigned from scratch. And you can immediately feel that difference in text rendering, layout generation, and poster design. Under the hood, it uses flow matching,'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it processes text and images together instead of separately. That gives it a much stronger understanding of where text should appear and why layouts remain more stable. On top of that, it uses Queen 3 VL as its vision language backbone,'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which makes prompt understanding feel far more natural than many local models. But, the most unique thing about Ideogram is its JSON-based control system. You can directly specify where text goes, what colors to use, which'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'regions contain images, and how the composition is structured. So again, it behaves much more like generating a design specification instead of simply generating an image. So, how do you actually use it? The'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easiest method right now is downloading the latest portable version of ComfyUI from GitHub. Go to releases and download version 0.24.0. At the time I\'m recording this video, the ComfyUI installer version still'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hasn\'t been updated to 0.24.0 yet, which means Ideogram support isn\'t available there yet. After downloading, extract the files, then open the template workflow. At that point, ComfyUI will prompt you to download the'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ideogram model. You don\'t necessarily need to use the official FP8 version because it may not be very consumer-PC-friendly. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Instead, you can open the Hugging Face integration inside ComfyUI and download'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the NF4 quantized version. That version allows Ideogram to run even on PCs with only 8GB VRAM. Yes, image quality may drop slightly, but we can recover a lot of that quality later'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using other techniques. One more important thing to mention, Ideogram currently uses a non-commercial license. That means research, experimentation, learning, and personal use are completely fine. But, if you plan to use'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated content commercially, make sure you carefully review the license terms first. At first glance, this workflow may look complicated, but it can actually be divided into a few simple sections. On'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the left, resolution control. In the middle, model loading and prompts. And on the right, sampling and generation. One unique thing about Ideogram is that it uses dual model CFG, and instead of'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'traditional clip, its backbone is Quinn 3 VL. That gives it dramatically stronger understanding of text and layouts compared to many other models. And that design philosophy also carries'

[06:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over into the workflow itself. One thing worth paying attention to here is that the workflow uses two separate nodes, CFG override and dual model CFG guider. What they essentially do is split CFG'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into different stages during sampling. In this setup, the first 70% of the steps use CFG equals 7, while the final 30% switch down to CFG equals 3. The advantage of this approach is that'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it reduces over-sharpening and color shifting during the later stages of generation, while also helping text rendering and fine detail converge more naturally. And honestly, [music] this reminds me a lot of the strategy'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'used in 1 2.2. Instead of trying to force every detail from the very beginning, the model first establishes the major structure and composition, then gradually refine smaller details afterward. In a way, it\'s actually pretty similar to how'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'humans observe images. We usually look at the overall scene first, then slowly focus on finer details. I think this kind of stage generation logic could become one of the major directions for both image and video generation models going forward.'

[07:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Another thing worth paying attention to is this preset JSON section below. Instead of using a single universal generation setup, Ideogram separates its workflow into three different generation strategies, quality, default, and turbo.'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the naming is pretty self-explanatory. If you want the best image quality, use quality. If you care more about generation speed, use turbo.'

[07:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you want a balance between the two, use default. What\'s interesting is that these presets don\'t just change the sampler name. They also adjust parameters like steps, moo, and stud together as a complete generation profile.'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s also why the official workflow doesn\'t recommend randomly mixing presets. But the thing that really separates this workflow from a typical comfy UI setup is this node right here. Ideogram 4 prompt builder KJ'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'At its [music] core, this is basically an AI design editor. With older models, you\'d usually type one huge paragraph prompt and hope the model understood what you meant. But this node is completely different. It actually lets'

[08:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you control layouts directly. At the top, you can define the overall theme and atmosphere. The background section controls the environment specifically. Below that, you can define visual style, lighting, medium type, and even brand'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'color palettes. If you work on posters or branding, I highly recommend setting the medium to graphic design because Ideogram responds extremely well to design-oriented descriptions.'

[08:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; But the real magic is this canvas section below. You can literally drag and position blocks. Each box represents an element inside the composition. For example, where the title goes, where the logo appears, where the CTA button'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should sit. You can even define this region is text, this region is the main visual. That\'s why Ideogram feels fundamentally different for poster design because now it actually has layout awareness.'

[08:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you don\'t want to handwrite JSON manually, the official workflow can even connect to a local LLM. You simply load a model through Ollama, connect the provided system prompt, and it can generate JSON prompts for you. Installing Ollama is very simple. You'

[09:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just need to search for it on Google, download it, and install [music] it. After the installation is complete, just make sure your settings are configured like this. For local models, I personally recommend Gemma 4 12B. It\'s lightweight enough'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that even an 8 GB VRAM PC can handle it. Overall, [music] the biggest difference with the Ideogram workflow isn\'t complexity. It\'s that so many previously manual adjustments are now structured and automated.'

[09:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Older ComfyUI workflows often felt like parameter gaming, but Ideogram feels more like executing a design specification. To see whether this model could realistically run on more consumer-level'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hardware, I tested it on one of my old PCs. It only has 8 GB of VRAM, 32 GB of RAM, and the GPU is an absolutely ancient 3050 OEM. And honestly, the results were better'

[10:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than I expected. As long as you set the megapixel value here to one, meaning a 1024 * 1024 output resolution, the workflow can run without hitting OOM errors.'

[10:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Wait, what? I asked you to generate a cat and you filtered it? From now on, I\'ll also try to test AI models on 8 GB VRAM GPUs whenever possible. Because I know most people don\'t really care whether a 4090 can run it, they'

[10:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'care whether their own PC can actually use it. And if you want to upscale images all the way to true 4K quality, you can check out my previous video covering Nvidia\'s latest technology,'

[10:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'PID. Of course, Ideogram 4 is powerful, but it\'s not a magic all-purpose model. What it truly excels at is posters, logos, brand visuals, layout design, and'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'UI mockups. Especially text rendering. It\'s honestly far more stable than many other models. But if you ask it to generate chaotic multi-character scenes, extreme action shots, music festival wide angles, or'

[11:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cinematic crowd compositions, you\'ll still end up re-rolling constantly. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; So, it\'s important to understand what this model actually is. At its core, this is a design-focused model, not a universal cinematic'

[11:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'storyboard engine. And again, it currently uses a non-commercial license. Research and experimentation are fine, but for commercial delivery, always confirm the licensing terms first. Finally, let\'s talk about the practical'

[11:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side. Cost. Cloud services like ideogram.ai or the official API are obviously the most convenient option. No model downloads, no comfyui setup, always running the latest version.'

[11:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But the trade-off is straightforward. Every image costs money. Local NF4 or FP8 workflows operate completely differently. Your main cost becomes the GPU you already own. After that, every additional image'

[12:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated costs almost nothing beyond electricity. And when you generate at scale, that difference becomes massive. My own workflow usually looks like this. Spam rerolls locally using turbo or default mode, find a strong composition,'

[12:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then switch to quality 48 for the final render. If commercial licensing or formal delivery is involved, then I switch back to the official hosted version. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; So, don\'t treat local and cloud'

[12:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation like a religion. What really matters is understanding where every dollar and every watt of power should be spent. And once you truly become comfortable with the local ideogram workflow, you\'ll stop burning API credits just to fix one typo on a'

[12:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'poster. All right, that\'s it for today\'s video. If you enjoyed the content, don\'t forget to like and subscribe. Your support is the biggest motivation behind my work. And I\'ll see you in the next video.'
